## GITOPS — ALL CHANGES GO THROUGH GIT

This cluster uses ArgoCD GitOps. The workflow is:
1. Edit YAML files in this repo
2. Commit + push to `master`
3. ArgoCD detects the change and syncs automatically

DO NOT suggest:
- `helm install` / `helm upgrade` (use ArgoCD Applications)
- `kubectl apply -f` for cluster resources that should be managed by ArgoCD
- Direct edits to the cluster outside of the GitOps workflow

Exceptions: one-off operations like creating secrets (secrets must NOT go in git).

## TALOS LINUX — NO SSH

- The M2 node runs Talos Linux. There is NO SSH.
- All node operations use: `talosctl --nodes 192.168.1.10`
- K8s API is at: https://192.168.1.10:6443
- Bootstrap token / talosconfig is in 1Password (not in this repo)
- The `talos/` directory contains schematic + Cilium values (safe), NOT secrets

## SECURITY — NEVER COMMIT SECRETS

The following must NEVER be committed to git:
- `talos/secrets.yaml`
- `talos/controlplane.yaml`
- `talos/worker.yaml`
- `talos/worker-gpu.yaml`
- `talos/talosconfig`
- Any Kubernetes secret YAML with actual credentials
- OAuth tokens, API keys, passwords of any kind

If you find any of these tracked in git, STOP and alert the user immediately.
Secrets belong in 1Password or as kubectl-applied K8s Secrets (not in this repo).

## CODE QUALITY RULES

1. YAML: Use 2-space indentation. Validate with `kubectl --dry-run=client` when possible.
2. Kustomize: Always include a `kustomization.yaml` in each directory with resources listed.
3. Helm values: Every `values.yaml` must have comments explaining what each section does.
4. ArgoCD Applications: Use `syncPolicy.automated` with `prune: true` and `selfHeal: true`.
5. Namespaces: Declare explicitly. Use `CreateNamespace=true` in syncOptions.
6. StorageClass: Default is `longhorn`. For single-node testing, 1 replica is fine.
7. app-of-apps/: This directory contains ArgoCD Application CRDs only (not regular K8s resources).
   ArgoCD scans it recursively (directory.recurse: true set in app-of-apps.yaml).
   Do NOT add kustomization.yaml here — ArgoCD handles discovery directly.
   Current apps: apps-prod/applications.yaml, prometheus-monitoring/base/prometheus-monitoring.yaml,
   simplefin-exporter/base/simplefin-exporter.yaml

## NETWORKING — SPECIFIC FACTS

- AT&T BGW320 has 1x 5 GbE LAN port + 3x 1 GbE LAN ports (NOT "4x 1 GbE" — this was WRONG)
- M2 has 2x 2.5 GbE NICs. Max per-port speed: 2.5 Gbps.
- LACP bonding M2's two 2.5 GbE ports = up to 5 Gbps AGGREGATE (not single-stream)
- GPU node NIC is 1 GbE only — bottleneck for any M2↔GPU transfers
- Tailscale direct connection: BGW320 forward UDP 41641 → 192.168.1.10
  (without this, Tailscale uses DERP relay — still works, slightly higher latency)

## RAM BENCHMARK CONTEXT

- M2 has 1x 32 GB DDR5-4800 SO-DIMM (single-channel)
- sysbench RAM result: ~9,593 MiB/s — this is EXPECTED for single-channel DDR5
- Adding a 2nd identical SO-DIMM enables dual-channel → ~19 GB/s (2x improvement)
- For accurate RAM benchmarks, prefer STREAM benchmark over sysbench
- Talos: run as a privileged K8s Job to access host memory bandwidth

## WHEN STUCK — DO THIS

1. Read the relevant file first: `read_file`, `grep_search`, `semantic_search`
2. Check running cluster state: `kubectl get` / `talosctl get`
3. Look at ArgoCD app status: `kubectl get application -n argocd`
4. Check docs: official Talos, Cilium, ArgoCD, cert-manager docs
5. If still stuck after 3 attempts, tell the user what you found and what is blocking you

## COMMIT MESSAGE FORMAT

```
<type>: <short description>

<optional body explaining why>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`, `security`, `infra`
Example: `feat: add simplefin Prometheus exporter with Grafana dashboard`
